6) The Geocentric model: This was a cosmological model of the universe that placed Earth at the center, with all other celestial bodies, including the sun, moon, planets, and stars, orbiting around it. This model was the predominant view held by ancient Greek astronomers. 7/8

5) Spontaneous generation: This idea, which claimed that living organisms could arise spontaneously from non-living matter, was a popular belief for much of human history. This idea was eventually disproven by experiments such as Louis Pasteur's swan-neck flask experiment. 6/8

4) Phlogiston theory: The Phlogiston theory was a popular theory in the 18th century that attempted to explain combustion. It claimed that a substance called phlogiston was released when materials burned, which was eventually proven to be false. 5/8

3) Steady State Universe: This theory of the universe was a popular cosmological model in the mid-20th century that proposed that the universe was eternal and unchanging. This theory was eventually disproven by the discovery of the cosmic microwave background radiation. 4/8

2) Lysenkoism: Lysenkoism was a pseudoscientific theory that was popular in the Soviet Union during the mid-20th century. It claimed that acquired traits could be inherited, which contradicted the principles of genetics. This theory was eventually discredited. 3/8

1) Phrenology: In the 19th century, phrenology was a popular pseudoscience that claimed that a person's character and mental abilities could be determined by examining the shape of their skull. This belief has since been discredited. 2/8

@kristahalt So perhaps efforts should be balanced in favour of building resiliency in the face of climate change that will inevitably come, rather than betting on being able to avert it. I'm not really thinking about this from the activist POV. Will keep reading your work with interest! 2/2

@kristahalt You're probably right. It's a very difficult collective action problem to get round given ever-growing demand for energy. I'm probably rather pessimistic, and I don't really see that we will resolve it. At least not within the ambitious time frames currently being discussed. 1/2

@StAndreasson I unfortunately don‚Äôt believe that ‚Äòthose in charge‚Äô have any plan for saving our society from climate disaster. So for the sake my future, and that of my future children, I will keep arguing that everyone needs to do what they can about climate change - and IOCs could do a lot.

@StAndreasson I think our biggest difference in opinion is not about economics - I agree completely - but responsibility and potentially the seriousness of climate change. Mitigating climate change is way more important that getting the highest possible short-term returns on investment.

@kristahalt I'll have to add, thirdly, that perhaps the only solution is a more radical skewing of incentives by means of legislation. But it's not always easy to win elections on such policies, no matter what the preferences of "environmentalists" may be. I don't envy those in charge!

@kristahalt However, the reason IOCs invest in oil and gas rather than renewables is because the former is profitable, and the latter not (cf. that Christophers article in NPE). That - normatively - a shift into green tech is desirable does not mean it is beneficial economically. 2/2

@kristahalt It's an important, and also very vexing question. I am not sure how we reduce global demand significantly in the short term as there is growing need for energy and renewables can only meet some of the growth in demand as opposed to significantly replace fossil fuels. 1/2

@StAndreasson So what should we do to reduce global demand? I believe that shifting capital away from fossil fuels to building green systems and infrastructure would be a great start. My tweet is primarily commenting on the short-termism of calling continued oil reliance 'good' for people.

@kristahalt Global warming is bad, but Shell cutting oil production won‚Äôt reduce global demand. Are we better off running the IOCs out of business and leaving NOCs to supply markets? It won‚Äôt improve the environment and may come with additional costs (economic and environmental).

What other options do we have? Agroecology is posed as an alternative to biotech that tackles the root cause of crises in food and climate: a decolonial project that promotes ecological diversity, situated knowledge, as well as power asymmetries and social injustices.

As @maywamontenegro argues, while ‚Äúsymptoms-level approaches may temporarily stymie a given problem, the risk is that financial investments, human resources, training and education go materially to serve stopgap solutions while structural malaise remains untreated.‚Äù
Some activists and scholars argue that since gene editing is a product of colonial-capitalist structures, it only tackles the symptoms, not the root causes of food and climate crises.

But with a handful of corporations owning 60 percent of the world‚Äôs seed supply, and agrochemical company DowDuPont holding the largest portfolio of CRISPR Intellectual Property (IP), will gene-edited seeds create the justice and equity we need for a sustainable future?

Gene editing is considered a solution to both mitigate and adapt to climate change in agriculture. In crops, it can be used to improve drought tolerance, and disease resistance and increase yields, without the need for chemical pesticides and fertilisers.

Humans have been altering plants for food, fuel and other purposes for millennia through traditional breeding techniques but in 2012, a team of biochemists from @UCBerkeley discovered how to directly edit the DNA of any cell using a system called CRISPR-Cas9.

While recognising the urgency of climate change actions, earlier policies focused predominantly on support through central government departments and on techno-managerial solutions. These were by and large apolitical and conflict blind.

"In the current situation in Myanmar there is an urgent need for international donors to rethink conventional climate change programming. This includes a critical reframing of the policies that were adopted by the civilian government prior to the military"

"Since the coup, regulatory and environmental oversight mechanisms have disappeared, meaning that local communities now have nowhere to take complaints about the effects of extractive projects on their land rights, local environment and livelihoods."

"The ability of local communities to mitigate and respond to climate change has been severely hampered by decades of authoritarian rule, agrarian land struggles and long running armed conflicts, which have worsened since the coup."

Myanmar provides evidence that climate change vulnerabilities cannot be attributed to global changes in temperatures and weather patterns alone, but also to issues related to governance, natural resource use and conflict.

"The violent reimposition of military rule has drastically undermined the civic space for environmental and climate justice actors, which during the 2011-2020 reform period provided some degree of protection to customary lands and the environment."

"Violent conflict and state oppression in Myanmar demonstrates the importance of placing conflict analysis and people-centred approaches at the centre of international programming on climate change and environmental protection."
